A chemical plant explosion in Jilin province, China, led to lethal chemicals contaminating the Songhua River.
The China National Petroleum Corp, responsible for the plant, faces scrutiny for the pollution.
Harbin, a city of 3 million, cut off water supply as benzene pollutants flowed downstream.
China informed Russia of the pollution, promising close cooperation.
Efforts to dilute the pollutants include increased water discharge from hydropower stations.
China vows to reduce emissions and prioritize pollution control in major rivers.
The focus is on minimizing the impact on Russia and ensuring public safety amidst the environmental crisis.
